Cradle
Cradle
Why...?
Confusion is evident in the girl's eyes as she walks through a desolate land. The ground is strewn with dust and sand, and weathered gravestones stand erect, scattered across the surface.
The human, whom she calls the "Curse Queller", has made their final choice.
The presence of the human has vanished, and the world that was created for that individual no longer has a purpose to exist.
Cradle
Why give up at the moment right before getting everything?
Cradle
Such an ending is not anticipated by anyone.
She whispers the question over and over, but the answer she longs for will forever elude her.
Cradle
...In the end, "I" still couldn't understand anything.
Cradle
But one thing remains certain—"humans" are a species that the more you study them, the more unfathomable they become.
She gazes upon this world teetering on the brink of its inevitable demise, silently awaiting her own ending.
However, a moment later, a faint smile graces her face.
Cradle
Not understanding anything doesn't mean this is a meaningless journey.
Assets/Product/Ui/Spine/UiSpine/UiMovieSpine/Rougae/UimovieRouge01/UimovieRouge01.prefab
She spreads out her skirt, gracefully lowering herself to the ground, knees bent and eyes closed.
She bows her head to the numerous gravestones.
Cradle
Thank you, for the time we spent together.
Cradle
For surpassing my expectations and continuously surprising me until the very end.
Cradle
I will hold every decision you've made close to my heart.
Cradle
I will cherish... no, make the most of everything I've gained from you.
Cradle
For calming the sound of tide on the planet, for that lives can bear greater fruits.
Cradle
For the next time... when "our" path and "yours" cross again.
With a heart filled with gratitude, she humbly pays her respects to the human across space.
Cradle
Oh... by the way.
Cradle
Please allow me to bid you farewell one last time on behalf of "myself."
Cradle
You... and "all of you," have created a...
Cradle
A fascinating story.
Later—
A gentle breeze caresses the girl's hair, causing it to dance in the air.
And dispersing this ephemeral dream that only exists in fleeting moments.

Lee
The examination on this area should be completed, Commandant.
Liv
The concentration of the remaining Punishing Virus has fallen below the safety threshold. It's confirmed that the Red Tide in this area has been out.
Good work, guys.
It's rare to see a Red Tide subside on its own.
Lucia
Indeed, no signs of Corrupted or Hetero-Creatures have been detected, which is quite unusual. But for the time being, I guess we can mark the area as "safe."
Lee
Other teams will be dispatched to conduct a more detailed examination. We're just here to scout.
Have we found anything?
Lee
Speaking of that... Liv found this in an abandoned building. Probably belonged to a Scavenger.
Lee hands you a well-worn camping backpack, where you only find a journal with its cover yellowed, a pen out of ink, and some rolls of moldy bandages remaining inside.
Liv
I tried to scan for any signs of life nearby, but unfortunately... its owner may have...
As you scan through the journal left by the unidentified Scavenger, you answer Liv with a nod of acknowledgment, indicating that she need not finish her sentence.
Lee
This place was flooded by a high-concentration Red Tide not long ago. The chances of human survival were almost negligible.
But at least this person left something behind.
Lucia
What's written in the journal?
Having reached the conclusion of the journal, you gently close its worn pages.
It's a "story."
Lee
A story? What kind of story?
...It's a bit complicated, hard to explain in a few words.
If you're interested, I'll ask WGAA to make some copies.
The mission is finished. Let's head back.
With utmost care, you return the journal to its rightful place and put on the backpack that once belonged to a stranger before leaving with your squad.
It is a story woven by the whims of an ordinary being who traversed through this desolate world.
The story, perhaps not captivating, may not be worthy of being read, analyzed, or praised.
But any story crafted with sincerity will always find its own "readers."
